January 1637","1661":"1661","1736":"1736","1637":"1637","1614":"1614","1702":"1702","La Broque, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France":"La Broque, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France","Schirmeck, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France":"Schirmeck, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"MICHEL","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Andre, Jacques, Micheline, Patrice, Dominique, Emile, Gisele, Laurent, Lucien, Philippe, Raymonde.","French, Walloon, German, Dutch, West Indian (mainly Haiti), Seychellois, and Mauritian: from the personal name <i>Michel</i> (see   Michael  ).","Basque: Castilianized form of <b>Mitxel</b>, from the personal name <i>Mitxel</i>, an equivalent of   Michael  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Michelle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Carlo, Gennaro.  French Colette, Odile.","French: from the feminine form of the personal name   Michel  , an equivalent of   Michael  .","Americanized form of Italian   Michele   or   Micheli   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"St. Michel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Gabrielle, Ovila.","French (<b>Saint-Michel</b>): habitational name from any of several places in various parts of France named Saint-Michel (from the dedication of their churches to Saint Michael), or a nickname with the prefix <i>Saint</i> as an (ironic) attachment to the personal name or surname   Michel  ."]},{"name":"Michael","meanings":["English, German, Dutch, Jewish, and Greek: from the personal name <i>Michael</i>, ultimately from Hebrew <i>Mika’el</i> ‘Who is like God?’. This was borne by an archangel in the Bible, the protector of Israel (Daniel 10:13, 12:1; Rev. 12:7). In Christian tradition, Michael was regarded as the warrior archangel, conqueror of Satan, and the personal name was correspondingly popular throughout Europe, especially in knightly and military families. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed many cognates from other languages, e.g. Hungarian <b>Mihály</b> (see   Mihaly  ), Czech and Slovak   Michal  , Assyrian/Chaldean or Arabic   Mikhael   and   Mikhail  , and also patronymics and other derivatives from these names, e.g. Greek   Papamichael  , its cognate <b>Papamichalis</b>, and   Michaelides  , Serbian <b>Mihajlović</b> (see   Mihajlovic  ), and Slovenian <b>Mihelčič</b> (see   Mihelcic  ). Compare   Mikeal  ."]},{"name":"Micheau","meanings":["French: variant or a pet form of the personal name   Michel   (see   Michael  ). Compare   Michaud   2."]},{"name":"Michau","meanings":["French: variant or a pet form of the personal name   Michel   (see   Michael  ).","Germanized form of Sorbian <b>Michał</b> ‘Michael’ (see   Michal  )."]},{"name":"Michaud","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Lucien, Andre, Benoit, Fernand, Normand, Ludger, Adrien, Philippe, Pierre, Camille, Henri.","French: variant or a pet form of the personal name   Michel   (see   Michael  ). Compare   Mishoe  .","Altered form of French   Micheau   and perhaps also of   Michaux  , both cognates of 1."]}]},{"name":"Marguerite","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Margaret  , also used in the English-speaking world, where its use has been reinforced by the fact that the name was adopted in the 19th century for a garden flower, a large cultivated variety of daisy. <i>Margaret</i> was earlier used in English as a dialect word denoting the ox-eye daisy, and the French equivalent was borrowed into English just in time to catch the vogue for deriving girls' names from vocabulary words denoting flowers.  See also  Daisy ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1670166,"age":45,"year":"1682","julianDay":2335399,"title":"The Palace of Versailles","description":"The Palace of Versailles was originally known as a hunting log and retreat for Louis XII. When Louis XIV took over he moved his family into it. After he died the palace was abandoned. It has since been turned into a museum.","url":"https://www.britannica.com/topic/Palace-of-Versailles","urlTitle":"Encyclopedia Britannica- Palace of Versailles","jurisdictionLevel":3}],"lifeSummary":"Marguerite MICHEL was born on 1 January 1637, in Schirmeck, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France as the daughter of Jean MICHEL and Chrestienne HENNOTTE. She married Thomas GARAT on 18 February 1659, in Schirmeck, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 4 daughters. She died on 1 January 1687, in her hometown, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1 janvier 1637–1 janvier 1687":"1. jaanuar 1637–1. jaanuar 1687","1637–1687":"1637–1687","1630–1699":"1630–1699","1620–Female":"1620–Surnud","1660–1690":"1660–1690","1661–1732":"1661–1732","1665–1736":"1665–1736","1670–1702":"1670–1702","–Female":"Surnud","1614–Male":"1614–Surnud","environ 1661":"umbes 1661","environ 1660":"umbes 1660","environ 1670":"umbes 1670","1682":"1682","1660":"1660","1670":"1670","1 janvier 1665":"1. jaanuar 1665","1 janvier 1687":"1. jaanuar 1687","1690":"1690","18 février 1659":"18. veebruar 1659","1732":"1732","1699":"1699","1665":"1665","1687":"1687","1620":"1620","1630":"1630","1 janvier 1637":"1. jaanuar 1637","1661":"1661","1736":"1736","1637":"1637","1614":"1614","1702":"1702","La Broque, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France":"La Broque, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, Prantsusmaa","Schirmeck, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France":"Schirmeck, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1 janvier 1637–1 janvier 1687":"1. tammikuuta 1637–1. tammikuuta 1687","1637–1687":"1637–1687","1630–1699":"1630–1699","1620–Female":"1620–Kuollut","1660–1690":"1660–1690","1661–1732":"1661–1732","1665–1736":"1665–1736","1670–1702":"1670–1702","–Female":"Kuollut","1614–Male":"1614–Kuollut","environ 1661":"noin 1661","environ 1660":"noin 1660","environ 1670":"noin 1670","1682":"1682","1660":"1660","1670":"1670","1 janvier 1665":"1.